## How does a website help an architecture firm win more projects?

I built Vistal a multi-page website that showcases their architecture projects, services, and design philosophy in a way that wins client trust before the first conversation. The site features project galleries, a full blog section, and service pages that communicate expertise at every scroll.

Vistal is an architecture and interior design firm that specializes in sustainable offices, shopping centers, urban retreats, and residential renovations. Their tagline says it all: "Your Gateway to Prestige Properties." They had the portfolio to back it up, but no website that did their work justice.

When a potential client searches for an architect online and lands on a website that looks like a generic template, they move on. For an architecture firm, the website itself is a design test. If it doesn't look polished, why would anyone trust you to design their building?

## What design approach works for an architecture portfolio?

I designed the site with large, full-width project images and generous spacing. Architecture is visual, so the website needs to let the work speak for itself. No cluttered layouts, no tiny thumbnails. Big images, clean typography, and smooth scroll animations using GSAP that reveal each section as you move down the page.

The homepage is structured in clear sections: hero with the firm's positioning, about section with key stats, featured projects with category tags like "Residential" and "Eco-friendly," a services breakdown, blog articles, FAQ, and a consultation CTA.

## How did I structure the services and project sections?

The services section highlights three core offerings: Functional Design, Renovation of Spaces, and Interior Design. Each service has its own image, description, and link to a dedicated service page. This makes it easy for visitors to find exactly what they need without scrolling through irrelevant content.

The project portfolio shows each completed project with a location tag, category labels, and a featured image. Visitors can see at a glance what types of work the firm handles and where they operate.

## Why did I add a blog section?

The blog section features articles on topics like "The Green Space Revolution," "Form Meets Function," and "Designing for Real Life." These articles do two things: they show visitors that Vistal thinks deeply about their craft, and they give Google more content to index. Over time, each article becomes a potential entry point from search results.

## What was the result?

The complete site was delivered in 2 weeks with a homepage, inner pages for services and about, project galleries, a blog carousel, FAQ section, and full SEO setup. Vistal now has a website that reflects the same level of quality and attention to detail that they bring to their architecture projects.
